Vote - Accept-Straight-to-Finalization - I asked N. Gonis for advice on this text and the suggested corrections. He kindly sent me the following notes. "We ought to have υἱ(οῦ) in 12, 210, 276, 279, 456; but in 457 we have ἐπὶ τὸν αὐ[τ(ὸν)], which suggests that the scribe intended the accusative, and this must have influenced the decision to produce these accusatives. If I were to edit the text, I would resolve υἱ(οῦ) throughout and correct the accusative in 457. εἰ(ς τὴν) (σάκε(λλαν) was not what the scribe intended, and the same applies to the editor (see 364 n.); ει/ = εἰ(ς). We have ει¯/ = εἰ(ς) τ(ὴν) only once, in l. 12 (for the abbreviation see P.Lond. IV p. 604 top); εἰ(ς) σάκε(λλαν) is a data entry error. Correct accordingly. The text needs checking; I've noticed some data entry errors but there may well be more: 216 δ(ιὰ) νο(μισμάτων) ϛ]γ: ϛ]γ → ξ]γ) 234 (πρώτου) (καὶ) (δευτέρας) κ(α)τ(α)βολῆ(ς): (πρώτου) → (πρώτης) 531 remove the question mark, and then replace πρ( )τ( ) with <:(πρ(o)τ(έρου))(?)|alt|(πρ(ώ)τ(ου)) (?):> (I'd rather have one of the two in the text than leave the word unrestored); 535 ἀν(τὶ) τ(οῦ) ἀποστρε(φθέντος) → <:(ἀντ(ὶ)) (|ἀποστρε|)|alt|(ἀντ(ὶ)) <τοῦ> (ἀποστρε(φθέντος))(?):> (the abbreviation used stands for ἀντί, not ἀντὶ τοῦ)." I have checked the volume and have nothing further to add. Carry out corrections as given by Berkes and Gonis.
